.SH NAME
Element.blur_event \- Element: blur event
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]blur\f[B]\f[R] event fires when an element has lost
focus.
The event does not bubble, but the related \f[CR]focusout\f[R] event
that follows does bubble.
.PP
An element will lose focus if another element is selected.
An element will also lose focus if a style that does not allow focus is
applied, such as \f[CR]hidden\f[R], or if the element is removed from
the document \[em] in both of these cases focus moves to the
\f[CR]body\f[R] element (viewport).
Note however that \f[CR]blur\f[R] is not fired when a focused element is
removed from the document.
.PP
The opposite of \f[CR]blur\f[R] is the \f[CR]focus\f[R] event, which
fires when the element has \f[I]received\f[R] focus.
.PP
The \f[CR]blur\f[R] event is not cancelable.
.SH SYNTAX
Use the event name in methods like \f[CR]addEventListener()\f[R], or set
an event handler property.
.IP
.EX
addEventListener(\[dq]blur\[dq], (event) \f[B]=>\f[R] {});

onblur = (event) \f[B]=>\f[R] {};
.EE
.SH EVENT TYPE
A \f[CR]FocusEvent\f[R].
Inherits from \f[CR]UIEvent\f[R] and \f[CR]Event\f[R].
.SH EVENT PROPERTIES
\f[I]This interface also inherits properties from its parent
\f[CI]UIEvent\f[I], and indirectly from \f[CI]Event\f[I].\f[R]
.TP
\f[B]FocusEvent.relatedTarget\f[R]
The element receiving focus, if any.
